THE RISK:
{
 "id": "framework-foreclosure-beachhead",
 "title": "The chosen beachhead buys through global frameworks: half the large-operator cell is not a market for a regional entrant",
 "narrative": "The venture's stated first channel is large operators, and the model gives that cell 40% of PDU spend on the logic 'large operators buy direct'. The corpus shows what 'direct' actually means at that scale: Digital Realty's $373M Schneider framework agreement, Iren's $1.6bn all-in Dell contract, PDU spend embedded as one line inside integrated rack/power/cooling packages. Combined with CR3 ≈ 0.55 among vendors who sell exactly those bundles, the buying event a new entrant needs — a discrete, multi-bidder PDU bake-off at a large operator — is disappearing. The only standalone PDU procurements found in the corpus were small, 1-2 bidder, sometimes explicitly sole-sourced. The beachhead the profile names is the cell most structurally closed to the venture; the model prices it as the biggest open door.",
 "category": "competitive",
 "targetNodes": [
  "cust.operator-large"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Large operators consolidate rack-power purchasing into multi-year global framework agreements and integrated vendor packages rather than discrete PDU line items — the exact procurement pattern documented in the cust.operator-large evidence trail",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "With the #1 vendor alone at 15.8% and a semi-consolidated top set (Schneider, Vertiv, Eaton, ABB, Legrand) selling bundled infrastructure, framework renewal — not open tender — becomes the default buying event; the residual standalone tenders observed were 1-2 bidder or sole-sourced ('No substitutions')",
   "refs": [
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c0",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c2",
    "ledger:shape.cr3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The 0.40 large-operator share — itself an unsourced internal estimate with no channel-split evidence — overstates the spend a regional entrant can actually contest; roughly half the cell is foreclosed behind frameworks the entrant cannot enter in year 1, and the venture's go-to-market points straight at it",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "profile:Product"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The founder's risk list treats 'large operators buy direct' as good news — direct means no distributor margin and a named buyer. The surface appearance of an accessible direct channel hides that 'direct' at hyperscale/large-colo means framework-direct: the door has a lock shaped like a 5-year global agreement, and the buyer's procurement team is contractually discouraged from running the bake-off the entrant's plan requires.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "Two named CE large operators (e.g., a Frankfurt or Amsterdam colo/hyperscale buyer) confirming a vendor-neutral, multi-bidder rack-PDU RFQ process in 2026 that is open to suppliers outside existing framework agreements.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.55,
  "rationale": "Framework consolidation at large operators is directly evidenced (Digital Realty-Schneider, Iren-Dell cases in the node's own tension trail), and the customerType split it undermines is admitted to be an unsourced internal estimate; uncertainty is only over the foreclosed fraction, not the mechanism's existence. [evidence revision: The framework/SCA consolidation mechanism is well corroborated by the Digital Realty–Schneider deal and vendor-concentration reports, nudging likelihood up. But the same SCA text explicitly preserves a 'dynamic, multi-vendor environment,' indicating frameworks are procurement structures rather than absolute foreclosures — and the SCA covers UPS/switchgear/skids, not PDUs specifically. This limits the upward revision. The falsifier was not found, so no downward pressure. Net: modest increase from 0.50 to 0.55.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.5
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "cust.operator-large",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.2,
   "note": "≈half of large-operator PDU spend sits inside global frameworks and integrated packages that a pre-launch regional entrant cannot contest; siblings deliberately not re-normalized — this is absolute foreclosure, not a mix shift"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "New or renewed multi-year power-infrastructure framework announcements by CE-active large operators",
   "where": "Digital Realty / Equinix / Vantage / NTT press releases and Schneider/Vertiv/Eaton earnings-call order-book commentary",
   "threshold": "≥2 new CE-relevant frameworks announced covering rack power",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Bidder counts and substitution clauses on standalone rack-PDU tenders",
   "where": "TED (Tenders Electronic Daily) award notices and operator supplier portals",
   "threshold": "Median bidders ≤2 or 'no substitution' language on >half of observed PDU line items",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Run the three CE operator/distributor procurement interviews the ledger already flags as pending, specifically instrumenting for framework coverage vs open-RFQ share of PDU spend",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "cust.operator-large",
   "note": "Directly de-risks the largest unsourced cell in the funnel; the interview guide should ask 'when did you last run a competitive PDU bake-off' not 'who do you buy from'"
  },
  {
   "action": "Re-sequence the beachhead to mid-size operators and enterprise retrofits, where discrete PDU purchasing survives, and approach large operators via second-source qualification inside existing frameworks rather than head-on displacement",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Second-source slots are the documented entry path for challengers in framework-dominated categories"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Schneider Electric and Digital Realty Announce $373M Supply Capacity Agreement",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Schneider Electric / PRNewswire",
   "date": "2025-11-19",
   "excerpt": "Digital Realty has signed a $373 million Supply Capacity Agreement (SCA) for UPS, Low Voltage Switchgear, and Pre-Fabricated Skids; the strategic shift to an SCA model provides guaranteed capacity while preserving flexibility for a dynamic, multi-vendor environment.",
   "url": "https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/schneider-electric-and-digital-realty-announce-373m-supply-capacity-agreement-to-meet-rising-data-center-demand-302620427.html",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Schneider Electric and Vertiv are Leading Players in the Data Centre PDU Market",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "MarketsandMarkets",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "Schneider Electric, Vertiv, Eaton, Legrand, and ABB are among the major players in the data center PDU market, expanding intelligent PDU portfolios through partnerships and integrated infrastructure offerings.",
   "url": "https://www.marketsandmarkets.com/ResearchInsight/data-center-pdu-companies.asp",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data Center Power - Market Share Analysis, Industry Trends & Statistics",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Mordor Intelligence / GII Research",
   "date": "2025-06-16",
   "excerpt": "Consolidation among equipment suppliers is reshaping electrical infrastructure priorities as hyperscale capacity additions push operators toward integrated, higher-voltage power trains.",
   "url": "https://www.giiresearch.com/report/moi1850125-data-center-power-market-share-analysis-industry.html",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.se.com/us/en/about-us/newsroom/news/press-releases/schneider-electric-and-digital-realty-announce-373m-supply-capacity-agreement-to-meet-rising-data-center-demand-691d192005c0c16f5902ca3c",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Digital Realty, (NYSE: DLR) the leading global provider of carrier-neutral data center, colocation, and interconnection solutions, has signed a $373 million Supply Capacity Agreement (SCA) for Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS), Low Voltage Switchgear (LVS), and Pre-Fabricated Skids"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/schneider-electric-and-digital-realty-announce-373m-supply-capacity-agreement-to-meet-rising-data-center-demand-302620427.html",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "The strategic shift to an SCA model provides guaranteed capacity, economies of scale, and a dedicated LVS production line, while preserving the flexibility needed for a dynamic, multi-vendor environment to mitigate risk."
  },
  {
